Washington County, Oregon

I am always curious about what is happening around me. I live in Hillsboro, a city situated in Washington County, I have chosen this county as my study area to analyze the spatial autocorrelation of median household income among these census tracts.

Moran’s I Scatter plot

Moran’s I scatter plot represents the correlation between a variable and the spatial Lag of the same variable.

Creating Census block group

cbg <- tidycensus::get_acs(
  geography = 'block group',
  year = 2020,
  state = 'OR',
  county = c('Washington'), # This can include multiple counties!
  variables = c("mhi_" = 'B19049_001'), # This can include multiple variables! And we can rename them!!!
  geometry = TRUE,
  output = 'wide'
) %>% 
  st_transform(3857) %>% # Project to something with better units (meters, in this case)
  filter(!sf::st_is_empty(.)) # Make sure we only have rows with geometries!

    lwd = 0.5,

    legend.position = c("left","bottom")

Creating Scatter Plot

moran_plot = function(var, w_var, xlab, ylab, main_title = NULL, normalize = T){
  if(missing(main_title)){
    main_title = "Moran's I Plot"
  }
  if(normalize){
    var = scale(var) %>% as.vector
    w_var = scale(w_var) %>% as.vector()
  }
  plot_dat = data.frame(var,w_var,stringsAsFactors = F)
  plot_dat %>% ggplot() +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0) +
    geom_point(aes(x=var,y=w_var), color='grey35') +
    xlab(xlab) +
    ylab(ylab) +
    geom_smooth(
      mapping = aes(x=var,y=w_var),
      formula = 'y ~ x',
      method = 'lm',
      color="grey10",
      size=1,
      lty = 2,
      se=F) +
    scale_color_manual(
      name = "", 
      values = c('HH'="firebrick",'HL'="brown1",'LL'="navy",'LH'="cornflowerblue")) +
    ggtitle(main_title)
}
moran_plot( var = cbg$mhi, w_var = cbg$lag_mhi, xlab = "dfd", ylab = "dce")
## Warning: Using `size` aesthetic for lines was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
## ℹ Please use `linewidth` instead.

Conclusion: This scatter plot shows positive spatial correlation meaning that similar values of the variable, median household income, are located in the same geographical location.

Global Moran’s I

c_test <- spdep::moran.mc(cbg$mhi, listw = cbg_W, nsim = 999, zero.policy = TRUE)
c_test
## 
##  Monte-Carlo simulation of Moran I
## 
## data:  cbg$mhi 
## weights: cbg_W  
## number of simulations + 1: 1000 
## 
## statistic = 0.32751, observed rank = 1000, p-value = 0.001
## alternative hypothesis: greater
plot(c_test,xlim=c(-0.5,1.0),xlab="Median Household Income")

Conclusion: In this density plot, the p-value is 0.001 < 0.5 considered as statistically significant. So here, we reject the null hypothesis.

Geris-Ord G

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = FALSE)
g_test <- spdep::globalG.test(x = cbg1$mhi, listw = cbg1_W)

## recommended (sepecially for distance bands)
g_test

##  Getis-Ord global G statistic
## 
## data:  cbg1$mhi 
## weights: cbg1_W 
## 
## standard deviate = 18.973, p-value < 0.00000000000000022

## sample estimates:
## Global G statistic        Expectation           Variance 
## 0.0012680318333870 0.0010515247108307 0.0000000001302176

Conclusion: In this Geris-Ord G analysis, the Global G statistics value is greater than the expectation value suggesting that there are potential hot spots in the data. Moreover, the p-value of this permutation is less than 0.05 also representing high values spatially clustered with each other.
